text:
Let's say you have a division statement. 
Which of these do you use?

Dividend / Divisor = Quotient 
or 
Dividend / Divisor = Quotient + Remainder

Follow-up Question:

Would you say: 
"The Quotient has a remainder of 0" 
or 
"The Statement has a remainder of 0"

#MTBoS

I have 6 one-fifths.

That‚Äôs two groups, each with 3 one-fifths.

The result requires I take 2 from each whole group of 3.

Because there are two of these groups, I get 2 one-fifths from each.

This results in 2 groups of 2 one-fifths: 4 one-fifths.

text:
So I understand the cringe moment from math teachers. This is not neat or tidy. 

But it /is/ mathematical.

I also understand that teachers brand this a "trick," but I wholeheartedly disagree with this.

Pushing on why we act the way we do is the exact opposite of a trick.
bbox_coords: NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
name: Nat Banting
description: MathEd (teaching, writing, speaking); @usaskEducation sessional; @FractionTalks curator; Co-editor: The Variable (@SMTSca); #MenuMath #FreeScalene. Wear a mask.

text:
It feels apparent to me that any mathematical action (or perhaps action in general) begins with deciding what scenario we are dealing with. 

This is often implicit. 

I think prompts like these work to make this important mathematical process explicit.
bbox_coords: NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
name: Nat Banting
description: MathEd (teaching, writing, speaking); @usaskEducation sessional; @FractionTalks curator; Co-editor: The Variable (@SMTSca); #MenuMath #FreeScalene. Wear a mask.

text:
I'm sure there are other things here, but what is striking me is that this problem isn't a "trick;" this problem is (purposefully) ill-posed. 

(what do we mean by speed? Pedalling "speed" or bike "speed"?)

This is not an accident, but a move with great pedagogical power.
bbox_coords: NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA

I want to know why this makes sense (because it sure feels like it does)
